(7. Understanding the Ubuntu server installer initramfs) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-04-26T02:49:11Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/linux/UbuntuServerInstallerInitramfs) Tj
T*
(I recently wrote about all of the various steps of a UEFI network install , where you have a) Tj
T*
(whole collection of DHCP, GRUB fetching things via TFTP and HTTP, and so on, all to boot into) Tj
T*
(your Ubuntu server install ISO image. Specifically, all of the GRUB stuff and much of the) Tj
T*
(complicated DHCP stuff is there because we have to load the installer's kernel and initial) Tj
T*
(ramdisk. Our primary usage for UEFI network installs is to reinstall physical servers that are) Tj
T*
(now in inconvenient locations, so eventually it occurred to me that if we already have running) Tj
T*
(Linux systems, there are simpler ways to boot into a specific kernel and initramfs with) Tj
T*
(specific command line arguments. One way is to add new GRUB boot entries, and another way is) Tj
T*
(kexec . If we're already using a local kernel and initramfs, it might be convenient to get rid) Tj
T*
(of the need for a DHCP server too, by copying the network parameters from the currently running) Tj
T*
(server and embedding them in both the kernel boot parameters and, more importantly, the) Tj
T*
(cloud-init files that the installer will use. To do this, we need to embed the cloud-init files) Tj
T*
(in the initramfs \(and then point to them with 'ds=nocloud;s=/whatever' in the kernel...) Tj
T*
