(8. How Bitwarden Encrypts and Decrypts Secrets) Tj
T*
(Source: Miguel Grinberg's Blog | Published: Sun, 26 Apr 2026 14:05:41 GMT) Tj
T*
(Link: https://blog.miguelgrinberg.com/post/how-bitwarden-encrypts-and-decrypts-secrets) Tj
T*
(As part of my efforts in reducing my dependency on Big Tech, I have been researching how to) Tj
T*
(self-host my password manager. One solution that looks very promising is Vaultwarden , an open) Tj
T*
(source clone of the Bitwarden cloud server. An interesting aspect of this server is that it) Tj
T*
(stores all the secrets in a standard SQLite database, so in addition to having the self-hosted) Tj
T*
(password server I could keep a backup copy of the database on my machine and query it directly.) Tj
T*
(But of course, the secrets are encrypted in this database, so they are useless unless I learn) Tj
T*
(how to decrypt them, similar to how the Bitwarden clients do it. Speaking of the Bitwarden) Tj
T*
(clients, while I was writing this article it came out that the official Bitwarden CLI client) Tj
T*
(was compromised in a supply chain attack. This is a tool that I personally use and have on all) Tj
T*
(my computers, so this feels like a wake up call to me. Luckily I did not install the) Tj
T*
(compromised version myself, but I think there is an argument to be made about rolling your own) Tj
T*
(secret management client instead of relying on the one all the hackers are after! In this) Tj
T*
(article I'll share how the encryption of secrets works in Bitwarden and its Vaultwarde...) Tj
